1.5  The Emergency Response Program

The Emergency Response Program is divided into two elements, as only properly trained and qualified personnel are authorized to respond to emergencies. Production workers contracted by YLLC are trained to notify and evacuate via the PlantA?s Emergency Action Plan. Only the Yuma Fire Department would respond to an emergency; support would be made available via WPS personnel trained to 29 CFR 1910.120(q) standards. Emergency equipment is maintained under the control of WPS. Written ammonia emergency procedures are detailed in the facilityA?s A?Thirty Minute PlanA?. Appropriate written plans are maintained on-site and updated on a regular basis. Local Emergency Response capabilities have been verified.


1.6   Planned changes to improve safety

The primary mechanisms to identify and plan safety improvements include (but are not limited to):
A?    Process Hazard Analysis revalidation/update;
A?    Compliance Audits;
A?    Routine maintenance (Mechanical Integrity Program);
A?    IIAR Bulletin 109 Inspections;
A?    WPS Inspection Protocol

Each of the Programs above may result in recommendations ranging from capital improvements to routine maintenance of the plant. Where necessary, Service Calls are established in parallel to identified needs. Current planned changes to improve safety include:
A?    Upgrade portions of the PlantA?s SOPA?s (include additional details);
A?    Check torque values on ceiling-mounted evaporator units;
A?    Increased awareness of Forklift Driver hazards;
A?    Check certain equipment for correct DOT labeling/placarding requirements.

Implementation of these measures has commenced according to the schedule set by the management of WPS.
